<h2>Overview</h2><p>The Barricade Rock Sliders installation is a prime example of a straightforward yet essential modification for Jeep enthusiasts who take their vehicles off the beaten path. Whether you’re crawling over boulders or navigating through tight trails, these rock sliders serve as a protective barrier for your Jeep's body and frame. This tutorial will guide you through the installation process, detailing necessary modifications and best practices to ensure you achieve a secure and functional fit.</p><h2>What This Covers</h2><p>In this article, we’ll explore:</p><ul><li>The tools required for installation.</li><li>Step-by-step instructions for mounting the rock sliders.</li><li>Additional modifications needed for long-arm suspension kits.</li><li>Helpful tips to avoid common pitfalls during installation.</li></ul><h2>Step-by-Step Breakdown</h2><p>Installing the Barricade Rock Sliders can be completed in a few simple steps:</p><ol><li><strong>Remove Body Mount Bolts:</strong> Start by safely lifting your Jeep and removing the body mount bolts. Be prepared; these bolts can be stubborn. Using a penetrating lubricant may help make this task easier. It’s important to take your time and avoid stripping the bolts.</li><li><strong>Install the Rock Sliders:</strong> Position the rock sliders under the vehicle and align them with the body mount points. Utilize a jack and a wooden block to support the sliders during the installation process. Be sure to check that nothing else obstructs the mount points.</li><li><strong>Secure Everything in Place:</strong> Reinsert the body mount bolts and ensure they are properly torqued. Note that there was some discrepancy in torque specifications — the recommended value for body mount bolts on a JK is often stated as 80 ft-lbs, but be sure to follow the provided instructions for your specific kit.</li></ol><h2>Modifications for Long Arm Kits</h2><p>If your Jeep is equipped with a long-arm suspension, some modifications to the rock sliders will be necessary. The rear control arm bracket may conflict with the slider bracket, resulting in a fitment issue. In this case, you’ll need to:</p><ul><li>Measure and mark the area on the slider bracket that needs to be modified.</li><li>Use a cutoff tool to trim the bracket while ensuring the cut is clean and provides sufficient space for movement when the suspension articulates.</li><li><strong>Protect Against Rust:</strong> After any cutting, be sure to repaint exposed metal to guard against rust, as unprotected areas can lead to long-term deterioration.</li></ul><h2>Helpful Tips</h2><p>Before you dive into the installation, here are a few tips to make the process smoother:</p><ul><li><strong>Have the Right Tools:</strong> Ensure you have a jack, socket set, cutting wheel, and thread locker on hand.</li><li><strong>Check Fitment:</strong> Do a dry fit of the sliders before fully securing them to avoid any unnecessary rework.</li><li><strong>Wear Protective Gear:</strong> Be sure to wear safety glasses and gloves, especially when using cutting tools.</li></ul><h2>Key Takeaways</h2><p>The Barricade Rock Sliders are a solid addition to your Jeep, providing protection and utility for serious off-road adventures. The installation process is relatively simple but does require some attention to detail, particularly when modifications for long-arm kits come into play. Following these steps and tips should help you achieve a successful installation. Happy wheeling!</p>

